<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08041c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08041c">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08041c"> 41(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> un homme si connu</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Cependant le coup manque. Alors les canailles s&apos;efforcent de nous mettre un autre bandeau sur les yeux, mieux attach&eacute;, opaque &agrave; souhait, plus r&eacute;sistant, d&apos;une efficacit&eacute; &eacute;prouv&eacute;e, convenant &agrave; tous les &acirc;ges et &agrave; toutes les conditions, le roi des bandeaux: l&apos;amour-propre. &ldquo;<mark>Un homme</mark> comme vous!&hellip; si sympathique!&hellip; si honorable!&hellip; <mark>si connu</mark>!&hellip; d&apos;une intelligence&hellip;&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[And still they don&apos;t succeed. The canaille then endeavour to give us another blindfold, better fixed, as impenetrable as possible, stronger, tried and tested, suitable for all ages and conditions, the king of all blindfolds: self-esteem. &ldquo;A man like you!.. so kind! ... so honourable! ... so well-known!... so intelligent...&rdquo;]</font> <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 304</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
